  "bib_entries": {
    "5867072": {
      "title": "Thiouracil antithyroid drugs as a new class of neuronal nitric oxide synthase inhibitors",
      "abstract": "Two established antithyroid drugs, 6-propyl-2-thiouracil and 6-methyl-2-thiouracil, as well as S-methylthiouracil, are shown to be competitive inhibitors of nitric oxide synthase (NOS) (KI values ranging from 14 to 60 μM), with moderate selectivity for the neuronal isoform. Other thioureylene and thioamide-containing heterocyclic systems proved virtually ineffective as NOS inhibitors. Besides offering novel useful leads for inhibitor design as well as to probe the active site of neuronal NOS, the results of this study may have interesting implications in relation to the antithyroid activity of thiouracils and their possible neurological effects."
    },
    "86091166": {
      "title": "Interaction of anticancer drugs with human and bovine serum albumin",
      "abstract": "Abstract The properties of 5-fluorouracil (5FU), 6-azauracil (6AU), 6-mercaptopurine (6MP), thiouracil (2TU) and thioimidazole (TI), as a quencher of fluorescence of tryptophanyl Trp 214 residue in serum albumin were studied. For the molar ratio [ligand]: [BSA]=30: 1 the decrease of protein fluorescence due to the presence of thiouracil as a quencher attains 90%, while imidazole derivative-thiamazole quenches the BSA fluorescence only by 25%. To estimate the character of the binding between studied quencher and human and bovine serum albumin the Scatchard and Stern–Volmer methods were used. The binding stoichiometry of allopurinol–mercaptopurine–serum albumin complex was studied."
    },
    "21604403": {
      "title": "The nature of the miscording caused by growth in the presence of 2-thiouracil",
      "abstract": "The effects of the pyrimidine analog, 2-thiouracil, on protein synthesis in enteric bacteria have been investigated in detail. The evidence presented indicates that under conditions of partial or complete uracil starvation 2-thiouracil is effectively incorporated into the RNA of either Salmonella typhimurium or Escherichia coli and that growth under these conditions leads to alterations in the structure of the proteins synthesized. Our results are consistent with the hypothesis that the alterations in the proteins are due to the partial replacement of uracil in messenger RNA by 2-thiouracil followed by misrecognition during translation. We suggest that 2-thiouracil in mRNA is frequently misread as C. The evidence to support this hypothesis is as follows. (1) 2-thiouracil is able phenotypically to suppress an ochre mutant in the his D gene of S. typhimurium , suggesting that the UAA codon is read as CAA. (2) 2-Thiouracil causes an increased incorporation of positively charged amino acids into polypeptide chains, a result that is shown to be consistent with the occurrence of phenotypic U→C transitions. Our results also compare the effects of 5-fluorouracil and 2-thiouracil, and show that both cause miscoding but differ in that 5-fluorouracil is bacteriocidal, whereas 2-thiouracil is bacteriostatic. This suggests that the killing effect of 5-fluorouracil may not be due to miscoding."
    },
    "61117786": {
      "title": "Principles of Nucleic Acid Structure",
      "abstract": "New textbooks at all levels of chemistry appear with great regularity. Some fields like basic biochemistry, organic reaction mechanisms, and chemical ther modynamics are well represented by many excellent texts, and new or revised editions are published sufficiently often to keep up with progress in research. However, some areas of chemistry, especially many of those taught at the grad uate level, suffer from a real lack of up-to-date textbooks. The most serious needs occur in fields that are rapidly changing. Textbooks in these subjects usually have to be written by scientists actually involved in the research which is advancing the field. It is not often easy to persuade such individuals to set time aside to help spread the knowledge they have accumulated. Our goal, in this series, is to pinpoint areas of chemistry where recent progress has outpaced what is covered in any available textbooks, and then seek out and persuade experts in these fields to produce relatively concise but instructive introductions to their fields. These should serve the needs of one semester or one quarter graduate courses in chemistry and biochemistry. In some cases the availability of texts in active research areas should help stimulate the creation of new courses. CHARLES R. CANTOR New York Preface This monograph is based on a review on polynucleotide structures written for a book series in 1976.\""
    }
  },
